{
  "text": "14 Isolates were screened for b-lactamase production by nitrocefin hydrolysis (Oxoid, Australia), in accordance with the manufacturer's instructions. Nitrocefin-positive isolates were tested for bla TEM and bla ROB genes using a multiplex PCR assay, which also produces different amplicon sizes for the different bla TEM promoters. [CITATION_1] The replicon type was determined by PCRs for integrative conjugative element-associated ORF51 and the rep gene for small plasmids, both as previously described. [CITATION_2] Isolates were screened for the presence of altered PBP3 using PBP3-S primers designed to amplify N526 but not N526K isolates, [CITATION_3] and isolates that failed to amplify had the transpeptidase domain of ftsI sequenced to confirm the BLNAR genotype, as previously described. [CITATION_4] Isolates were assigned to one of the following genotypes: no resistance genes, b-lactamase negative ampicillin susceptible (gBLNAS); positive for b-lactamase genes, b-lactamase positive ampicillin resistant (gBLPAR); positive for the N526K substitution in PBP3, b-lactamase negative ampicillin resistant (gBLNAR); and positive for b-lactamase genes and the N526K substitution, b-lactamase positive amoxicillin/clavulanate resistant (gBLPACR). [CITATION_5] Notably this PCR algorithm does not include R517H-positive isolates in the gBLNAR/gBLPACR genotypes, as no PCR primers have yet been designed for this genotype. [CITATION_6] ",
